Germany: A costly budgetary fetish
FRANKFURT – The European Central Bank (ECB) is facing fierce attacks in Germany, a country that has long prided itself on upholding the principle of central bank independence.
In fact, it was Germany that insisted that this principle be incorporated into the criteria set out in the Maastricht Treaty, which defines the conditions for membership in the European Monetary Union.
For many members of the Economic and Monetary Union (EMU), granting independence to their central bank as a condition for joining the eurozone entailed a political regime change.
Thus, the independence of the Banque de France during the referendum on ratifying the Maastricht Treaty in 1992 was one of the strongest arguments against adopting the euro in the campaign.
In today's Germany, however, it has become commonplace, if we can say so, to put pressure on the central bank.
For several months now, even the Finance Minister, Wolfgang Schäuble, has been regularly commenting on the monetary policy of the European Central Bank (ECB).
Schäuble's interventions target the very core of what constitutes central bank independence.
While he does not seek to redefine the monetary policy objective (that "price stability" objective, in the old Bundesbank jargon), he nonetheless provides advice on the tools the ECB should use and how it should handle them to achieve such an objective.
We know of precedents.
In 1998, Oskar Lafontaine, then German Minister of Finance, offered his advice to the first President of the ECB, Wim Duisenberg, on how to conduct monetary policy (Lafontaine’s goal was to ultimately create a target zone for exchange rates).
Duisenberg, with his typically Dutch reticence, replied that there was nothing incongruous about a politician expressing an opinion on monetary policy (in Germany, this was absolutely unusual). “Yet,” he added, “it would be entirely abnormal to take [his] suggestions into account.”

The respect for the independence of monetary policy has long been a central element of Germany’s Stabilitätkultur (‘culture of stability’).
The founding act of the Bundesbank’s reputation for strict independence was its refusal to yield to Chancellor Konrad Adenauer’s urging in 1956 to contain rising interest rates.
At that time, France saw things differently.
Charles de Gaulle was about to create the Fifth Republic, with the Bank of France reporting to the Minister of Finance.
But it was another time.
Following various crises that shook the ECU, monetary policy has increasingly tended to replace fiscal policy.
Has the old doctrine become outdated?
The EU remains very vulnerable; the median EU citizen has already lost ten years, and more alarmingly, we are close to a critical situation.
The US, however, is doing better.
Despite difficult-to-manage political blockages, they have managed to address the macro-economic problem (weak global demand) by launching expansionary fiscal and monetary policies.
The US also handled their banking problems better, which were initially much worse than in Europe.
There is clearly a strong interaction between measures that can be taken in both areas.)
The stronger an economy is, the more profitable its banks are, and the better they are able to fulfill their function: financing the economy.
But the independence of the ECB is less threatened by the sound advice of a finance minister than by the lack of public support.
In fact, the famous autonomy of the Bundesbank relied less on its legal status than on the unwavering support (justified by its performance) of German citizens.
This is exactly the opposite for the ECB.
Voices are being heard, especially in Germany, calling for it to be subjected to greater pressures.
But the greatest threat to the ECB's autonomy lies in the unbearable burden placed on its shoulders.
The less budgetary policy is called upon to stabilize output, the more central banks are effectively forced to take on this objective (unless, of course, they are designed to let things take their natural course and allow the economy to stagnate, or worse).
The political outcome of this chain of events is a clear regression towards nationalism, both right and left, in all EUM countries, including Germany.
The rise of nationalism is almost a logical corollary to the policies pursued.
It is endogenous.
And here too, Germany leads the way, with its obsession with the schwarze Null, budget balance, come what may.
In Germany, deficits are viewed negatively, not only arithmeticly but also morally, even though this defies economic common sense and appears to be clientelism.
In the late 19th century, leading German public finance specialists such as Albert Schäffle and Adolph Wagner forged a "golden rule" according to which current expenditures should, on average, be financed by current revenues.
Public spending, and the resources it requires, justify themselves through their usefulness.
This amounts to saying that investments aimed at improving productivity – capital expenditures – can be financed with debt, the servicing of which is ensured by growth in revenues and the base associated with those revenues.
This classical approach has been institutionalized in a useful concept: the distinction between current expenditures and investment spending, which is still practiced at the municipal level in Germany (and Austria).
This is crucial because in Germany, about 50% of public investment spending is managed at this level (the proportion has been decreasing, as the municipal share was two-thirds at the beginning of the 1990s).
These expenditures are consistent with supporting the competitiveness of German small and medium-sized enterprises (mittelstand).
However, compared to the early 1990s and at constant prices, investment spending has fallen by about 15%.
For more than a decade, they have been insufficient to maintain the stock of capital.
If this is not how we prepare for the future, then we undermine productivity and prosperity.
In brief, the black zero goes against the intended goal.
Old infrastructure (not as much as in the United States) has become a real problem for Germany.
Moreover, the fiscal frugality of German leaders extends beyond German borders, and its effects are amplified by the monetary union, which lacks exchange rates to accommodate national peculiarities.
Of course, the European Monetary Union is imperfect.
But blaming the only institution willing to "do what needs to be done" to get the UEM back on track is a very bad idea.
Allowing countries to use, where it exists, the fiscal space they have to reduce pressure on the ECB would be a much better strategy.
Germany, without a doubt, enjoys some room for maneuver in this regard.
